 and that's how we talk to databases,

5
00:00:10,560 --> 00:00:13,320
 and it's beautiful because it allows portability

6
00:00:13,320 --> 00:00:15,720
 up to a point across databases,

7
00:00:15,720 --> 00:00:19,420
 and we talked about all the CREATE TABLE stuff,

8
00:00:19,420 --> 00:00:22,720
 and so this is just a bit of review where, you know,

9
00:00:22,720 --> 00:00:26,760
 we can type these commands to SQLite, we run SQLite,

10
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:28,800
 we run a CREATE TABLE statement,

11
00:00:28,800 --> 00:00:31,560
 and, you know, we do it, and it's a dot tables that we go,

12
00:00:31,560 --> 00:00:33,000
 we can ask kind of schema users,

13
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:36,120
 we did all this in a previous lecture,

14
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:39,120
 and so that's basically how SQL works,

15
00:00:39,120 --> 00:00:43,900
 and here's a series of SQL commands from a previous lecture,

16
00:00:43,900 --> 00:00:47,260
 just kind of as review, it's pretty simple, CRUD.

17
00:00:47,260 --> 00:00:50,600
 Now, one of the problems is, as I mentioned,

18
00:00:50,600 --> 00:00:53,960
 is that different databases like Postgres and MySQL

19
00:00:53,960 --> 00:00:55,460
 do all this stuff identical,

20
00:00:55,460 --> 00:00:59,160
 but then some more subtle things like how foreign keys work,

21
00:00:59,160 --> 00:01:03,560
 which we'll learn in a bit, or how they do limits,

22
00:01:03,560 --> 00:01:06,960
 like pulling like 25, next 25, next 25,

23
00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:09,200
 that's a little bit different,

24
00:01:09,200 --> 00:01:11,200
 and so if you want to build an application

25
00:01:11,200 --> 00:01:14,160
 that talks across more than one database,

26
00:01:14,160 --> 00:01:16,160
 you've got to think a little bit,

27
00:01:16,160 --> 00:01:17,960
 and one solution to this,

28
00:01:17,960 --> 00:01:22,100
 also to kind of limit the fancy SQL you have to learn,

29
00:01:22,100 --> 00:01:26,260
 I like to say that you can learn the first 60% of SQL

30
00:01:26,260 --> 00:01:29,860
 in about three hours,

31
00:01:29,860 --> 00:01:34,060
 and the last 40% is literally a lifetime,

32
00:01:34,060 --> 00:01:37,400
 and so advanced SQL is difficult to do,

33
00:01:37,400 --> 00:01:42,460
 it's really hard to teach a class in advanced SQL,

34
00:01:42,460 --> 00:01:44,360
 I can teach you advanced features,

35
00:01:44,360 --> 00:01:46,200
 but then there are so many features

36
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:48,060
 that you just can't learn in a class,

37
00:01:48,060 --> 00:01:49,660
 because which database you're using,

38
00:01:49,660 --> 00:01:52,600
 and they're different for every database.

39
00:01:52,600 --> 00:01:56,200
 So one thing that's happened in the past decade or so

40
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:59,900
 is the emergence of what's called Object Relational Mappers,

41
00:01:59,900 --> 00:02:03,360
 and that is to, you have the physical database layer,

42
00:02:03,360 --> 00:02:05,800
 and then you have SQL, which is an abstraction,

43
00:02:05,800 --> 00:02:07,900
 it's a imperfect abstraction,

44
00:02:07,900 --> 00:02:10,560
 and then Django builds another abstraction on top of that

45
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:12,000
 called Object Relational Mappers,

46
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:15,200
 so we just create a Python object,

47
00:02:15,200 --> 00:02:17,360
 and we ask that to be placed in the table.

48
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:20,800
 Now, the object may have a name and an email address,

49
00:02:20,800 --> 00:02:23,700
 and a birthday or something in it,

50
00:02:23,700 --> 00:02:25,920
 it can have all kinds of data in that object,

51
00:02:25,920 --> 00:02:29,200
 and then that maps into a name and an email address,

52
00:02:29,200 --> 00:02:32,260
 and we have to tell it, do we want this to be indexed,

53
00:02:32,260 --> 00:02:33,360
 and all these other kinds of things,

54
00:02:33,360 --> 00:02:35,220
 we communicate through the ORM,

55
00:02:35,220 --> 00:02:37,160
 so we leave the ORM alone.

56
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:40,320
 Now in Django, as we get more advanced,

57
00:02:40,320 --> 00:02:42,260
 you can also sort of bypass the ORM,

58
00:02:42,260 --> 00:02:46,360
 because the way the objects are mapped into the tables

59
00:02:46,360 --> 00:02:50,500
 is predictable, the names of the columns is predictable,

60
00:02:50,500 --> 00:02:54,760
 and so it's kind of like it's a shortcut for,

61
00:02:54,760 --> 00:02:58,360
 I like to think it's like the 80% of the most common things

62
00:02:58,360 --> 00:02:59,800
 you do with a database are easily done

63
00:02:59,800 --> 00:03:03,760
 with an object-relational model, but object ORM,

64
00:03:03,760 --> 00:03:08,760
 but ultimately, once you get to the more advanced things,

65
00:03:08,760 --> 00:03:11,060
 you tend to not be able to do that with an ORM,

66
00:03:11,060 --> 00:03:14,100
 you get to the point where writing the SQL

67
00:03:14,100 --> 00:03:15,460
 is easier than using the ORM,

68
00:03:15,460 --> 00:03:17,960
 but for about 80%, writing ORM code

69
00:03:17,960 --> 00:03:20,200
 is way easier than writing the SQL.

70
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:24,220
 The other thing that ORM does is it allows you to

71
00:03:24,220 --> 00:03:30,420
 have multiple databases, because the ORM code inside of Django

72
00:03:30,420 --> 00:03:35,560
 knows the difference between SQLite, Postgres, and MySQL,

73
00:03:35,560 --> 00:03:38,820
 and so you could actually start an application

74
00:03:38,820 --> 00:03:40,860
 that uses SQLite during all your development,

75
00:03:40,860 --> 00:03:42,220
 and then when you're devoted to production,

76
00:03:42,220 --> 00:03:43,320
 you just go like, you know what,

77
00:03:43,320 --> 00:03:46,060
 let's just use MySQL or Postgres instead,

78
00:03:46,060 --> 00:03:47,260
 and that's quite cool.

79
00:03:47,260 --> 00:03:51,220
 I find them limiting, and so just I want you to know

80
00:03:51,220 --> 00:03:54,400
 both how to use objects and how to use SQL,

81
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:56,560
 but understand that most of what you're going to do

82
00:03:56,560 --> 00:03:58,360
 is to use the object-relational mapping,

83
00:03:58,360 --> 00:04:02,360
 and we get a lot of power with this.

84
00:04:02,360 --> 00:04:07,260
 So if we look at sort of the way we communicate

85
00:04:07,260 --> 00:04:09,760
 to the database or the way we define the database,

86
00:04:11,060 --> 00:04:16,060
 in SQL we create a table, and that right there is portable,

87
00:04:16,060 --> 00:04:18,520
 but once you start doing things like adding

88
00:04:18,520 --> 00:04:20,160
 auto-increment columns and things like that,

89
00:04:20,160 --> 00:04:23,920
 it stops being portable, and so that's the way we do it,

90
00:04:23,920 --> 00:04:26,820
 but in Django, the way we do this is we have a file

91
00:04:26,820 --> 00:04:31,820
 called models.py, and it's in the application folder,

92
00:04:31,820 --> 00:04:34,700
 and then we are going to use object orientation,

93
00:04:34,700 --> 00:04:37,900
 so we're gonna, from Django.db, that's a package,

94
00:04:37,900 --> 00:04:42,800
 we're gonna import models, and models is now a class,

95
00:04:42,800 --> 00:04:45,420
 and we're gonna create a class called user,

96
00:04:45,420 --> 00:04:49,560
 this is going to be equivalent to the name of the table,

97
00:04:49,560 --> 00:04:53,660
 and we're going, and the definition,

98
00:04:53,660 --> 00:04:56,000
 we're gonna extend models.model,

99
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:59,120
 and so there's a lot of, this is called extending,

100
00:04:59,120 --> 00:05:03,000
 it's called inheritance, we're gonna get a lot of features

101
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:05,760
 and functionality, excuse me.

102
00:05:08,900 --> 00:05:10,760
 We're gonna get a lot of features and functionality

103
00:05:10,760 --> 00:05:14,320
 from this code, so there's probably 20,000 lines

104
00:05:14,320 --> 00:05:17,100
 of fancy code that we didn't write that we're using

105
00:05:17,100 --> 00:05:20,520
 by extending models.model, we're getting all that,

106
00:05:20,520 --> 00:05:22,800
 and then within here we create a couple of attributes

107
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:25,260
 that basically says give me a character field,

108
00:05:25,260 --> 00:05:29,520
 models is a class, char field is a method within that class,

109
00:05:29,520 --> 00:05:32,920
 max length equals 128, and that gives us the name.

110
00:05:32,920 --> 00:05:35,860
 These two things are equivalent, and what happens is,

111
00:05:35,860 --> 00:05:37,900
 is when we build this, and we do what's called

112
00:05:37,900 --> 00:05:41,220
 run a migration, then Django will make this table for us,

113
00:05:41,220 --> 00:05:44,320
 but then we have this abstraction that we can use

114
00:05:44,320 --> 00:05:45,460
 to talk to it.

115
00:05:45,460 --> 00:05:49,560
 So this is called a migration, and so you have to be

116
00:05:49,560 --> 00:05:54,060
 in the projects folder, and so once you create a migration

117
00:05:54,060 --> 00:05:58,860
 inside of your Django application, then you go up

118
00:05:58,860 --> 00:06:02,100
 into the Django project, and you say python3 manage.py,

119
00:06:02,100 --> 00:06:06,560
 now manage.py is kind of like the thing that starts

120
00:06:06,560 --> 00:06:10,760
 everything, so make migrations is actually creating files,

121
00:06:10,760 --> 00:06:14,320
 'cause the idea with migrations is that you would debug

122
00:06:14,320 --> 00:06:17,580
 your migrations on your development environment,

123
00:06:17,580 --> 00:06:20,760
 and then once you know, you would move them to production.

124
00:06:20,760 --> 00:06:23,000
 So you'd make the migrations in development environment,

125
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:24,920
 you'd get them right, and then you'd check them

126
00:06:24,920 --> 00:06:27,680
 into GitHub perhaps, and then in production,

127
00:06:27,680 --> 00:06:30,120
 you would pull your migrations out of GitHub,

128
00:06:30,120 --> 00:06:34,280
 and then the migrate, so the make migrations,

129
00:06:34,280 --> 00:06:37,940
 the make migrations bit, that is creating a set

130
00:06:37,940 --> 00:06:40,920
 of migration scripts, and you can see that it's making

131
00:06:40,920 --> 00:06:42,660
 these files, and they're actual files, and you can go

132
00:06:42,660 --> 00:06:45,920
 find those files, like 001 initial py,

133
00:06:45,920 --> 00:06:48,680
 and then the migrate is reading the migrations,

134
00:06:48,680 --> 00:06:51,640
 and then actually changing the database.

135
00:06:51,640 --> 00:06:54,300
 So that's the one where you might be able to make

136
00:06:54,300 --> 00:06:56,860
 a migration, and it doesn't matter what database

137
00:06:56,860 --> 00:06:59,560
 you're gonna use, could be your development in SQLite,

138
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:04,460
 production in MySQL, you would do migrate in both of those,

139
00:07:04,460 --> 00:07:07,260
 and in your development, it would make an SQLite database,

140
00:07:07,260 --> 00:07:09,440
 and in your production, it would make an MySQL database,

141
00:07:09,440 --> 00:07:12,760
 put the tables in, and the SQL might even be quite subtle,

142
00:07:12,760 --> 00:07:15,040
 and it will be subtly different between them,

143
00:07:15,040 --> 00:07:17,600
 but you don't care, so migrate is the act

144
00:07:17,600 --> 00:07:19,760
 of creating the database.

145
00:07:19,760 --> 00:07:22,200
 Now, in our development environments,

146
00:07:22,200 --> 00:07:26,240
 we're gonna be creating a file called db.sqlite3,

147
00:07:26,240 --> 00:07:28,720
 and so if you get all messed up, you don't have

148
00:07:28,720 --> 00:07:30,700
 to remake your migrations, they're just sitting there

149
00:07:30,700 --> 00:07:32,820
 kind of as part of your source code,

150
00:07:32,820 --> 00:07:35,700
 and you can get rid of the db.sqlite3 file,

151
00:07:35,700 --> 00:07:39,520
 and then run the migrations again, if you get kinda messed up.

152
00:07:39,520 --> 00:07:42,620
 So the make migrations reads this,

153
00:07:42,620 --> 00:07:44,220
 and creates these other little files.

154
00:07:44,220 --> 00:07:46,160
 You can take a look at 'em, they're kind of like

155
00:07:46,160 --> 00:07:48,200
 Django's internal files, they're Python,

156
00:07:48,200 --> 00:07:51,180
 it's just you're not gonna write them by yourself,

157
00:07:51,180 --> 00:07:54,840
 but then the migrate reads the 001 initial dot py,

158
00:07:54,840 --> 00:07:57,540
 and then actually creates SQL commands,

159
00:07:57,540 --> 00:08:00,380
 and runs those SQL commands for us.

160
00:08:00,380 --> 00:08:03,580
 And so if we jump after we've done this,

161
00:08:03,580 --> 00:08:07,580
 we see this file db.sqlite3, and we can jump in

162
00:08:07,580 --> 00:08:10,160
 and take a look, again, you have to be in the right folder,

163
00:08:10,160 --> 00:08:13,560
 so you'd be in the Django_projects,

164
00:08:13,560 --> 00:08:15,160
 and then the folder of the project,

165
00:08:15,160 --> 00:08:17,280
 but there'd be a file called db.sqlite3,

166
00:08:17,280 --> 00:08:22,160
 go into a Linux command line, type sqlite3, db.sqlite3,

167
00:08:22,160 --> 00:08:24,480
 and you will find a whole bunch of things.

168
00:08:24,480 --> 00:08:26,780
 And when you go into sqlite and you type .tables,

169
00:08:26,780 --> 00:08:29,980
 you will see that Django has a bunch of migrations

170
00:08:29,980 --> 00:08:33,300
 that are all there from the sessions,

171
00:08:33,300 --> 00:08:34,820
 and stuff we're gonna learn how to use later,

172
00:08:34,820 --> 00:08:36,700
 authorization, et cetera, et cetera.

173
00:08:36,700 --> 00:08:39,860
 But then the particular data model that you created,

174
00:08:39,860 --> 00:08:43,820
 which is a user data model, there's a table in there for that.

175
00:08:43,820 --> 00:08:47,380
 And if we use the schema command of sqlite3,

176
00:08:47,380 --> 00:08:49,180
 and we say, hey, what is in that user model

177
00:08:49,180 --> 00:08:53,320
 underscore user table, and it's a create statement, right?

178
00:08:53,320 --> 00:08:55,520
 And so this is the actual create statement

179
00:08:55,520 --> 00:09:00,520
 that the Django sent to sqlite to create the table.

180
00:09:00,520 --> 00:09:02,740
 And I was talking about some of these things

181
00:09:02,740 --> 00:09:03,660
 are quite predictable.

182
00:09:03,660 --> 00:09:05,340
 The name of the column is quite predictable,

183
00:09:05,340 --> 00:09:06,940
 ID, name, email, et cetera.

184
00:09:06,940 --> 00:09:09,180
 It asks the ID field for you automatically.

185
00:09:09,180 --> 00:09:10,420
 And most of it's portable,

186
00:09:10,420 --> 00:09:12,020
 like this part here is quite portable,

187
00:09:12,020 --> 00:09:15,520
 but this ID statement here, primary key auto increment,

188
00:09:15,520 --> 00:09:18,380
 turns out that if you're in MySQL, or Oracle,

189
00:09:18,380 --> 00:09:21,640
 or Postgres, or sqlite, that's a little different,

190
00:09:21,640 --> 00:09:24,200
 but literally the migrate takes care of all that,

191
00:09:24,200 --> 00:09:26,300
 because the migrate knows that thing,

192
00:09:26,300 --> 00:09:27,900
 and as MySQL changes,

193
00:09:27,900 --> 00:09:30,260
 that particular syntax doesn't change very much,

194
00:09:30,260 --> 00:09:33,860
 but as MySQL changes, then the Django stuff changes,

195
00:09:33,860 --> 00:09:36,000
 and it all kind of works out.

196
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:38,580
 And so you can sort of run these commands,

197
00:09:38,580 --> 00:09:40,340
 and then sneak back into the database,

198
00:09:40,340 --> 00:09:41,480
 and you can see what they've done,

199
00:09:41,480 --> 00:09:44,380
 but it's all very predictable.

200
00:09:44,380 --> 00:09:50,140
 I'm gonna spill my coffee on my computer.

201
00:09:51,020 --> 00:09:55,020
 So you can also talk, you're talking at the low level

202
00:09:55,020 --> 00:09:56,340
 when you're running the sqlite command,

203
00:09:56,340 --> 00:09:57,820
 but you can also be in that folder,

204
00:09:57,820 --> 00:10:02,020
 same folder that has db.sqlite and manage.py,

205
00:10:02,020 --> 00:10:04,280
 and then you can start what's called the shell.

206
00:10:04,280 --> 00:10:06,160
 So this is different than the Linux shell,

207
00:10:06,160 --> 00:10:07,180
 and you see the prompt change

208
00:10:07,180 --> 00:10:10,240
 from dollar sign to three chevrons.

209
00:10:10,240 --> 00:10:13,980
 And it's not the same as the Python shell,

210
00:10:13,980 --> 00:10:16,480
 although it is the same as the Python shell,

211
00:10:16,480 --> 00:10:19,140
 with a whole bunch of Django libraries that are pre-mounted.

212
00:10:19,140 --> 00:10:22,380
 Okay, and so if you just say Python three,

213
00:10:22,380 --> 00:10:24,700
 you'll get this, but this next command

214
00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:27,540
 that is from user model, models, import user,

215
00:10:27,540 --> 00:10:31,460
 that will fail unless you let manage.py start your shell,

216
00:10:31,460 --> 00:10:34,340
 because again, it loads a bunch of objects

217
00:10:34,340 --> 00:10:36,500
 and classes into your space,

218
00:10:36,500 --> 00:10:39,040
 and then all of a sudden user model.models works,

219
00:10:39,040 --> 00:10:41,640
 users there, et cetera, okay?

220
00:10:41,640 --> 00:10:46,640
 So this is pulling from your models.py file that you built,

221
00:10:47,800 --> 00:10:50,860
 and so user model is the application name,

222
00:10:50,860 --> 00:10:53,160
 and models is the models.py file,

223
00:10:53,160 --> 00:10:56,380
 we import the user model, which is in this case a class,

224
00:10:56,380 --> 00:11:01,020
 user is a class, and we're going to do a constructor call.

225
00:11:01,020 --> 00:11:03,340
 And so we're gonna say, let's make a new user,

226
00:11:03,340 --> 00:11:07,160
 set the name to Kristen and the email to that email,

227
00:11:07,160 --> 00:11:09,820
 and this actually has not done anything in the database,

228
00:11:09,820 --> 00:11:13,940
 this creates, in effect, just a Python variable,

229
00:11:13,940 --> 00:11:16,740
 and then to force it to be written to the database,

230
00:11:16,740 --> 00:11:19,580
 we call u.save, and so save is a method

231
00:11:19,580 --> 00:11:22,700
 on this new user object, capital user,

232
00:11:22,700 --> 00:11:26,740
 capital user is a class, we're using a constructor

233
00:11:26,740 --> 00:11:29,980
 to construct from the class an actual instance, an object,

234
00:11:29,980 --> 00:11:32,340
 and then we get that into u, the instance object,

235
00:11:32,340 --> 00:11:35,740
 and then that object sits in our memory until we say save,

236
00:11:35,740 --> 00:11:38,080
 and then it also pushes it back to the database.

237
00:11:38,080 --> 00:11:40,080
 Now one of the things that the save does,

238
00:11:40,080 --> 00:11:44,500
 it assigns, in effect, a serial number, or a row ID,

239
00:11:44,500 --> 00:11:46,580
 if you look at these, they start pretty predictably

240
00:11:46,580 --> 00:11:49,020
 at one, two, three, four, five, but if you're getting

241
00:11:49,020 --> 00:11:50,980
 a bunch of things coming in from a bunch of places,

242
00:11:50,980 --> 00:11:55,220
 then the database just assigns each object, each row,

243
00:11:55,220 --> 00:11:58,820
 and that's part of that whole auto increment thing,

244
00:11:58,820 --> 00:12:02,220
 come on, go back up, this whole auto increment thing,

245
00:12:02,220 --> 00:12:05,380
 that says, hey database, I'm gonna put your records in,

246
00:12:05,380 --> 00:12:06,980
 I'm gonna give you the name and the email,

247
00:12:06,980 --> 00:12:09,940
 and you come up with a number, but then when you're done,

248
00:12:09,940 --> 00:12:12,420
 I want you to tell me what the number is,

249
00:12:12,420 --> 00:12:14,260
 and this is how you get that number,

250
00:12:14,260 --> 00:12:16,020
 by saying, oh, print u.id.

